169. Majority Element
Problem

Given an integer array:

nums[]

Find the element that appears more than:

⌊n/2⌋

times.

You may assume that the majority element always exists.

Approach 1 — Sorting
Intuition

After sorting, the majority element will always be present at the middle index.

Because it appears more than half of the array.

Example
Input
nums = [2,2,1,1,1,2,2]

After sorting:

[1,1,1,2,2,2,2]

Middle index:

nums.length / 2 = 7 / 2 = 3

Element at index 3:

2

Answer = 2

Java Code
import java.util.Arrays;

class Solution {
    public int majorityElement(int[] nums) {

        Arrays.sort(nums);

        return nums[nums.length / 2];
    }
}
Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity

Sorting takes:

O(n log n)
Space Complexity
O(1)

(depends on sorting implementation internally)

Why Middle Element Always Works?

Majority element frequency is:

>n/2

So after sorting, it must occupy the middle position.

Optimal Approach — Moore’s Voting Algorithm
Intuition

Different elements cancel each other.

Since majority element appears more than all others combined, it survives all cancellations.

Main Idea

Maintain:

candidate → possible majority element
count     → support count
Rules
If count == 0

Choose current element as new candidate.

If current element == candidate
count++
Else
count--

Different elements cancel each other.

Dry Run
Input
nums = [2,2,1,1,1,2,2]
Step 1

Current = 2

candidate = 2
count = 1
Step 2

Current = 2

Same element.

count = 2
Step 3

Current = 1

Different element.

count = 1
Step 4

Current = 1

Different again.

count = 0

All previous support cancelled.

Step 5

Current = 1

New candidate.

candidate = 1
count = 1
Step 6

Current = 2

Different element.

count = 0
Step 7

Current = 2

New candidate.

candidate = 2
count = 1

Final answer:

2
Optimal Java Code
class Solution {
    public int majorityElement(int[] nums) {
      Arrays.sort(nums);
      return nums[nums.length/2];
    }
}
Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity
O(n)
Space Complexity
O(1)
Important Interview Point

Moore’s Voting works because majority element frequency is:

>n/2

So it can never be completely cancelled out by other elements.
